captions.text: [MUSIC PLAYING]
LAUREN FRODERMAN: We're back!

I can't believe we're
back here already.

JESSE: I'm ready this
time to go ham.

LAUREN FRODERMAN: I feel like
the last time, you weren't too

psyched about the whole
basketball thing, and neither
were the judges.

They were, like, it
was distracting.

And so I want to give you
something that you can leave
and be, like, awesome!
JESSE: I'm excited.
LAUREN FRODERMAN: Like, god!

I definitely am going
to challenge you.
JESSE: I'm ready.

LAUREN FRODERMAN: I'm
going to push you.
JESSE: I'm ready.

It was awesome to see Lauren
again, and she's really got me

excited about this whole thing,
because I think she

kind of heard some
of my concerns.

LAUREN FRODERMAN: Did anybody
say anything back home?

JESSE: My dad, he's a
big PvP [INAUDIBLE]

peep as it is, so he's really
watching the videos, and he

saw the performance,
and he said what?

I know you're way better
than that.
He was a little disappointed.

LAUREN FRODERMAN: Oh, that
makes me so sad.

JESSE: That just makes me
want to push harder.

See, my dad was just honest, and
he knows I'm better than I
did on this last performance.

LAUREN FRODERMAN: I want
you to be a bouncer.

I'm going to be the girl trying
to get into the club,

and then we kind of
go in like battle.

There you go, just
like you wanted.

JESSE: This one, she
has it set up.
We're going to battle.

That's something I know how to
do, that's what I do in the

club, as I love battling
people.

So hopefully, it
will look good.

And I got a good idea already
for the D-Trix challenge.
LAUREN FRODERMAN: Oh, you do?

JEANA: So what is this
D-Trix challenge?

I'm hearing about it, but
I don't know about it.
What is it?

JESSE: One of us has to stay off
the ground for longer than
an eight count.

How long is usually
an eight count?
It all depends on the beat?
LAUREN FRODERMAN: Yeah.

I feel like they're going
to judge on creativity,

personally, because it's easy
for anybody to be lifted for
an eight count.

You just cradle them,
spin them around.

JESSE: You can lift up on my
arms, and then make it look
like you're gliding.
LAUREN FRODERMAN: I'm nervous.
JESSE: Nervous.

LAUREN FRODERMAN: This
is the song.
[MUSIC PLAYING]

LAUREN FRODERMAN: So this will
be like the beginning, with me

trying to get in, and
you're, like, no.
You're not on.
JESSE: OK, OK.

When I first heard the song,
it was like really slow, a

girl singing, and I'm like,
whoa, what's going on here?

This isn't Chester
See performance.

But then I heard
the beat drop.
LAUREN FRODERMAN: [INAUDIBLE].
Then we really bust it out.
And this is like our battling.
JESSE: Oh!

It's got a really good
rhythm to it,
so it's dough freshness.

Yes, I like it, I like
it, I like it.

She actually told me that we're
going to be highlighting

some of my signature moves, the
dough fresh as you know,

my little pancake, the
woo tang, probably,
and some other things.
So it's going to be cool.

LAUREN FRODERMAN: You can
totally be the hot girl that
goes in before me.

You could totally just, like,
strut your stuff,
and he could be like--
JEANA: I can't strut my stuff.

LAUREN FRODERMAN: All you
got to do is walk.
Would you be down?

Take like three walks towards
him, do a little wave, hi.
He unlatches the thing.
There we go.

Spin on the inside,
there we go.

JEANA: I couldn't help but have
a little prank for him.

I was trying my worst to not get
through it nicely, and I
did terrible.

I kept spinning the wrong way
on purpose, and he's just
didn't care.

And I'm, like, what
is going on?

JESSE: Just think about me
going this way, that way.
JEANA: So unnatural?
JESSE: Yes.
JEANA: How do you do it?
Teach me.

JESSE: Are you trying
[INAUDIBLE].

LAUREN FRODERMAN:
How do you walk?

I mean, how do you
normally walk?

JESSE: I can walk
like a chick.

JEANA: And Jesse was actually
being very supportive, trying

to help me do these dance
moves and teach me
which way to go.

He was coaching me, like pulling
me so I turn the right

way, and I'm turning the
wrong way on purpose.

And it was just frustrating,
because I'm trying to make you

mad, and it was a little
fail, I guess.

JESSE: It's only $100,000
if you ruin it, but
it's not a big deal.

Remember, you get one of these
possibly if you twirl good.

LAUREN FRODERMAN: I think we
could do it, you guys.
JESSE: Pinkie swear?
JEANA: Pinkie swear what?

JESSE: You're not trying
to prank me somehow?

JEANA: The pinkie swear is like
something I hold down,
like that's serious with me.
I don't lie if I pinkie swear.

So I was secretly holding my
bag and crossing these two

fingers under it, and
he didn't see it.

I don't know if anybody else
saw it, either, but I did.

It was not even a full cross,
because it was like half a
cross, so it was good enough.

JESSE: I don't ever know when
I'm getting pranked, so if it
is a prank.

LAUREN FRODERMAN: I liked the
idea of having Jeana in the

beginning, but now that I know
she was pranking us, I don't

know if she's comfortable
with it.

Like, I don't know if that's
really what she wanted.

Because I was kind of getting
committed to the idea.

It's like, yeah, that
would be cool.

JESSE: I was almost, like, what,
and then, all right, I
guess she got it.

LAUREN FRODERMAN: But
now, I don't know.

And now, I don't
know she can--

because if she can actually
walk, then I do want her to do

it, but if she can't
walk, maybe not.
JESSE: She can walk.

She just can't chew gum
at the same time.

LAUREN FRODERMAN: Forward
with your feet.
Forward, forward.
JESSE: Forward, forward.

LAUREN FRODERMAN: Exactly,
exactly.
And make it manly.
But you'll go right, left.
There you go.

And then you're going
to go out, out.
Baum, bam.
And make it manly.
JESSE: What the F?

LAUREN FRODERMAN: So you
want to go lean,
there you go, and lean.

JESSE: Lauren keeps telling me
to make it manly, which I

don't think I have a problem
with, because when she did

this one move like this, and she
had to be like a girl, I
already killed it.
Like, I was already--
I can't be womanly if I tried.
Womanly?
Is that a word?
I can't be girly if I tried.

LAUREN FRODERMAN: And
make it manly.
There it is, there it is.
It's very groovy.
There we go.
Close, close, close, close.
Lean, and lean.
Then right, right.
Yeah.

JESSE: I don't know why I'm
having problems with that.

Yeah, like, when we're doing
this move right here, Lauren
can bend, like, a lot more.
Like, that's it.
That's all I got, right there.
And she's, like, 90 degrees.

So for me to try and put my
own stank on it, it was
getting a little difficult.
But I think I got it now.
I think I worked it out.

LAUREN FRODERMAN: Eight,
walk, walk, bend, bend.
That was better.

Here, I'll show you
with music.
It's very fast.

I'll show you what hopefully
we will both be doing.
[MUSIC PLAYING]
JESSE: I like that one.

This was, like, boom, boom,
boom, boom, and
that's that I like.
LAUREN FRODERMAN: OK, cool.

I'll show you for
full out now.

JESSE: I'm going to
be practicing
this all night tonight.

LAUREN FRODERMAN: From the
bounce bounce, you're going to
kick out, in.
Yeah.

So it goes bounce,
bounce, kick in.
Yep.
So, bounce, bounce, kick in.
JESSE: Can I do a salute?
LAUREN FRODERMAN: Yeah.
JESSE: That'd be dope.

LAUREN FRODERMAN: So we'll go,
bounce, bounce, kick, salute.

JESSE: So when Lauren told me
this move, and then we moved

it into something else,
I was, like, we
should just pop a salute.
So of we can salute the troops,
the dough fresh nation.

We're going ham, and then
we're going ham
again in the routine.

So all you guys, that's
for you guys
out there, the salute.

LAUREN FRODERMAN: You're
going to facing
be facing this direction.
JESSE: This direction.

LAUREN FRODERMAN: Yep,
you're going to
be facing this direction.

I need you to have to your feet
out together in a wide

enough stance that I'm going to
jump on you and you're not
going to fall.

JESSE: So when we're going to do
the hold when Lauren jumps

on my shoulders, she told me she
knew what she was doing.
This was all good.

LAUREN FRODERMAN: So I'm going
to jump, and you're going to
throw off of me.
JESSE: Then I'm going to go--
LAUREN FRODERMAN: Yes.

But I have to hook my legs
for just a second so
that I can arch back.

JESSE: So she jumps
on my shoulders.

She tells me to throw
her hands off.

She didn't really explain it
definitely how she was going
down, and I did that.

LAUREN FRODERMAN: Oh god,
I'm going to die.
JESSE: Are you hooked?
Oh my God, are you hooked?
And all I hear is, poop!

It sounded like she just
nailed the ground.
[SLOW MOTION SOUNDS]
JESSE: You went for it!
LAUREN FRODERMAN: I did!
JESSE: Are you all right?
She went ham.
She went ham.

LAUREN FRODERMAN: So I jump on
you, go back and through, and

then you want to grab me,
exactly, and then kick, kick,
kick, kick, kick.
Yeah!
Yeah, yeah, yeah, yeah, yeah.
And, eight!
And grab me, go!
Good.
Jump on.
And, kicking.
Good.
That was really good.
JESSE: It's tough.
LAUREN FRODERMAN: Is it scary?

JESSE: It's something that
I feel we could mess up.

LAUREN FRODERMAN: All right,
well, let's focus.
We're going to kick butt.

We actually got a
lot of practice.
JESSE: And I love it.

I love the routine, I love the
song, and I think it's going
to be awesome.

I love how you're pushing
it like crazy fast.
LAUREN FRODERMAN: Yay!
[MUSIC PLAYING]
